Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations unsettled large parts of Asia.
A year earlier, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly grandiose "State Visit Plus" to Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric would finally be a thing of the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the US "strategic engagement" in China with "strategic competition."
Added to this is the fact that the US, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year earlier.
Today, there is great uncertainty in financial markets, with growth slowing in China and Europe and higher interest rates starting to take effect in America.
The uncertainty about the future development of nuclear talks with North Korea also clouds the picture.
So what are the prospects for US-China relations in 2019?
It is likely that by March there will be an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make in this regard.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If tariffs are negotiated one after another, a year could pass.
If Chinese economic reformers, however, adopt a more drastic approach by, over time, pledging the abolition of all tariffs and asking Americans to do the same, a quicker result could be achieved.
This would, however, run counter to Chinese trade officials, who have been trained for decades to give little, let alone everything, all at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Nevertheless, reform is something different from the way contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there should be no specific provisions on technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the administration of President Barack Obama could be renewed.
Nevertheless, their enforcement or legal action in cases of intellectual property rights violations remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to subject relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international arbitration in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically entrusted with the enforcement of intellectual property protection.
If China objects, it could develop its own international commercial arbitration system based in China.
For this, however, qualified foreigners would need to be appointed to its arbitration panel in order to strengthen international credibility.
No one has confidence in Chinese commercial courts.
In order to meet its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent commercial and civil chambers within its judicial system, even if the criminal court remains under political control.
American concerns regarding state subsidies under China's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be resolved.
The fact is that all countries provide a certain level of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we prescribed a maximum level of state support for a particular company, it would be difficult to assess compliance.
I am not confident that there will be an agreement in this area.
Perhaps America must simply outmaneuver China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China may offer tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
Thus, China might decide in the course of time to take the drastic step of agreeing on tariff-free trade not only with the United States, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would have a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as a promoter of global free trade and to curb the trend towards protectionism.
As part of such a shift, China could ask the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) for admission, in order to overtake the United States (which exited the trade agreement as one of Trump's first official actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably light-footed when it discovers a political opening and market access.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations regarding China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the United States, China is likely to be committed in its general foreign and security policy in 2019 to resolving conflicts in its relations with other countries.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from Japan's coast guard indicates a significant reduction in Chinese incursions into the territory of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also aims to reduce tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations regarding the South China Sea by accelerating negotiations on a "Code of Conduct."
Furthermore, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, considering the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports Taiwan's independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the United States continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the United States continue to occur in the South China Sea, and the conflict could escalate if the United States more forcefully emphasizes its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Across all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its grand project, the "New Silk Road."
However, in recent months, the initiative has generated less political fervor in China.
Among Chinese officials, discussions have already begun regarding the revision of certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota Port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns regarding the long-term financial viability of the New Silk Road.
In 2019, triumphant reports on the New Silk Road may therefore be less frequent to hear.
Furthermore, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It will probably continue to appear as a new advocate of the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More cautious representatives of China's foreign policy establishment consider it better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially when the United States shows consistent disregard for them.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the United States and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership is likely to use the year 2019 to form a well-founded judgment about the future of U.S. policy: The consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new U.S. strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that America's attitude towards China has fundamentally changed, they are still uncertain about the exact form this change will take and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
